\subsection{Impact of Ionized Gas on Magnitudes and Colors}

Figure~\ref{fig3} shows the spectral features captured by the UVIS and HRC filters in the galaxies NGC 1566 (left panel, $Z=0.014$) and NGC 5253 (right panel, $Z=0.004$), as illustrated using 3\,Myr-old Pn models at the redshifts of the galaxies. The vertical axes of both panels use arbitrary units but identical scaling factors. Differences between the two spectra arise from the dependance of stellar evolution on metallicity. In particular, the ionizing rate at 3 Myr is higher at low compared to high metallicity due to hotter O stars and less dense winds. Note the relatively stronger collisionally-excited oxygen lines at low metallicity compared to high metallicity. This is because at low $Z$, the interstellar gas temperature is higher because of decreased cooling from metals \citep{cha01}. As can be seen in Fig.~\ref{fig3}, the use of F550M instead of F555W for NGC 5253 avoids contamination of broad-band photometry by strong H$\beta$ and [O{\sc\,iii}] lines at the redshift of this galaxy.





